[A] Health Canada
Update 30 - Severe acute respiratory syndrome 14 Apr 2003 5:00 PM
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/sars/update30.html>
Latest Canadian Numbers on SARS
As of 14 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 287 probable or
suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Canada. There
have been 13 deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have occurred in persons
who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS cases in the household
or in a health-care setting.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
(These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM EDST 14 Apr 2003.)
Ontario is reporting 100 probable and 136 suspect cases. All cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 3 probable and 36 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.
So far, 85 people have been discharged from hospitals in Ontario. These
people were treated as suspect cases or as probable cases.
[B] Epidemiologic analysis (as of 13 Apr 2003)
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030413_e.html>
[In the epidemic curve presented on this webpage, the most recent date of
onset of illness in a case reported is 8 Apr 2003.
A review of this curve suggests that the transmission rate is slowing down
to one or 2 new cases a day since 2 Apr 2003. It is too early to state
with certainty that another generation of cases might not appear over the
coming week. *** see news brief [7][B] below for breaking news of possible
new generation of cases in the community.***
Additional data presenting the outcome of the probable cases can also be
found on this website. As of 13 Apr 2003 there were 13 deaths out of 97
reported probable cases (case fatality rate 13.7 percent) and out of a
total of 283 probable and suspected cases (case fatality rate 4.6
percent). Most of the deaths occurred in individuals with underlying
disease, and nearly all were in individuals over 70 years of age. - Mod.MPP]
