[7]
Date: 14 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News briefs
[A] Italy from Ultimo Segundo, Brazil
<http://ultimosegundo.ig.com.br/useg/mundo/artigo/0,,1168155,00.html>
A 56-year-old man died today in a hospital in Naples, 10 days after
returning from trip to Asia. It is possible that this will be the first
death attributable to SARS in Italy.
[B] Canada from CTV,
<http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1050363196324_22/?hub=Canada>
[ProMED-mail would like to thank Joanne Silberner of NPR for alerting us of
this breaking news. - Mod.MPP]
According to documents obtained by CTV News that were circulated among
health officials on Sunday and Monday, SARS infections have been spreading
among "a religious group associated with the Centenary/funeral home case."
The "Centenary funeral home case" refers to one of the original SARS
infections in Toronto. A person infected with SARS was known to have
visited a local funeral home, and people who had visited that funeral home
were asked to be on the lookout for symptoms of SARS. Those cases were
apparently misdiagnosed when they originally turned up in family medical
practices and emergency rooms, rather than being screened through the SARS
clinics that had been set up in the past 2 weeks. The misdiagnoses raise
the possibility that the infections have spread further into the general
population.
"Some of these cases were initially given a diagnosis other than SARS
despite multiple visits to hospital emergency rooms," according to a Sunday
memo by Dr. Sheela Basrur, Toronto's chief medical officer. "This was due
to the apparent lack of a clear epidemiological link to a known SARS case."
[C]
More information from the Toronto Star: 14 Ap 2003 08:44 PM
<http://www.thestar.com/NASApp/cs/ContentServer?pagename=thestar/Layout/Article_Type1&c=Article&cid=1050357706691&call_pageid=968332188492&col=968793972154>
Canada's SARS crisis deepened tonight when public health officials
announced a new cluster of possible cases among a tight-knit religious
community in Toronto that are linked to the funeral of a SARS [case] 2
weeks ago. There are 10 probable and 19 suspect cases among the community,
Dr. Sheela Basur, the city's chief medical officer of health, told an
evening news conference. Basur wouldn't identify the group involved due to
privacy concerns. The cases stem from a funeral 1 Apr 2003 at the Highland
Funeral Home in east-end Toronto for someone who died of SARS.
"There are some 500 active members (of the community); of them, 29 members
have either probable or suspect SARS and an additional 2 are not members of
this group but worked closely with one of their members." All of them have
been ordered into quarantine.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Today's global update on cumulative reported cases and numbers of new
cases reported since date of last WHO update reflects 2 days of reported
activities, as the last WHO update was 2 days ago, on 12 Apr 2003. Hence,
before one is alarmed by an apparent major increase in daily case reports,
one needs to keep this in mind. What further highlights this is the daily
updates from Hong Kong and Singapore, (both of which issued reports
yesterday) where the increase in cases reported since yesterday is 40 and 7
respectively, in contrast with the 82 and 11 respectively presented in the
WHO Global update table in [1][A]. As noted in the WHO update statement
(see [1][C], Indonesia, the Philippines and Sweden have been added to the
list of countries reporting probable cases, whereas Japan has been removed
from the list as the previously reported cases were found to have other
explainable etiologies for their SARS-like illness. A further reminder of
the challenges in relying on reports of a disease that is currently purely
based using a case definition with clinical and epidemiologic criteria
rather than a laboratory confirmed diagnosis. Hopefully, with the addition
of the more senstive PCR testing due to be released later this week, we may
be coming closer to a conclusion that the newly identified unique
coronavirus is in fact the etiologic agent of SARS, and that we will have
sensitive laboratory diagnostic testing that will allow for the additional
case reporting category of "laboratory-confirmed" cases.
Other questions that are raised in today's report is the mention of 3
deaths in younger, healthy individuals reported in Hong Kong, and the
question of what might predispose to more severe illness in this age
group. One wonders what other factors may have contributed here. A
reminder is the "historical" information that paramyxoviruses were isolated
from some of the earlier patients in Canada, Germany, and Hong Kong, and in
one of the specimens processed in the USA (there was no mention as to the
origins of the specimen). Were these isolates coincidental? Or, is it
possible that coinfection leads to a more severe progressive respiratory
disease and compromise as well as potentially leading to the observed
phenomenon of "super spreaders." In the case of coinfection with human
immunodifficiency virus (a member of the Retroviridae) and hepatitis C
virus (a member of the Flaviviridae), a more rapid progression of liver
disease to severe liver damage is observed, hence there is a precedent for
a potentiation of disease with active coinfection of 2 different viral
organisms.
The late-breaking news from Canada on the possibility of community-based
spread outside of the previously defined groups is disconcerting. As this
news just hit the newswires, and we are about to go to press, there are
many questions on this report that may be addressed in information due from
health officials later on. The story as presented in the above news brief
[7][B] suggests that there had been misdiagnosed cases that were seen by
health professionals and were not subjected to infection control measures
to try to limit the spread to additional cases. There is mention of
multiple visits to emergency rooms and to private health practitioners, so
the possibility of yet another generation of cases among those health care
personnel having seen these cases is of concern. The news brief also
mentions that the spread may involve a closed group of individuals, but
more information on this was not available at this time. We await more
information on this, preferably from official sources. - Mod.MPP]
